{"title_page": "Rally Trans Itapua", "text_new": "The '''Rally Trans Itapua''', is an international [[rally racing]] event based in the [[Itap\u00faa Department]] in south-east [[Paraguay]]. The event is the opening round of the [[Codasur South American Rally Championship]] and a round of the Paraguayan Championship, the [[Campeonato Nacional Paraguayo]].\n\nThe event was first run in 1981 and ran only briefly until 1983 as political instability swept Paraguay. Restart in 1989, the event has run continuously since then apart from a brief rest in 2004-05. The event became international in 2010 when it replaced the [[Rally de Encarnaci\u00f3n]] as Paraguay's rally on the CODASUR championship. Paraguayan drivers have won every event, even after the influx of international drivers of recent years. In particular the Galanti brothers have dominated the event. [[Alejandro Galanti]] has won the event seven times between 1998 and 2012 while older brother [[Marquito Galanti]] has taken four wins. All eleven victories were in Toyotas, spanning Group A, WRC and most recently Super 2000 technical regulations cars. 2008 saw Paraguay's first CODASUR champion Victor Galeano win the event. In 2013 triple Codasur champion [[Gustavo Saba]] finally broke through for a popular win at his home event.\n\n==List of winners==\nSourced in part from:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rally.com.py/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/itapua-2014.pdf |title=El Rally Trans Itap\u00faa, una prueba con historia |trans-title = The Rally Trans Itapua, a test with history |year=2014 |website= rally.com.py |publisher=Campeonato Nacional Paraguayo |lang = es |format=PDF |accessdate=2014-04-22 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year!!Winner!!Car\n|-\n| 1981\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Santiago Silguero]]\n| [[Nissan Violet#A10|Datsun 160J]]\n|-\n| 1982\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Santiago Silguero]]\n| [[Nissan Violet#A10|Datsun 160J]]\n|-\n| 1983\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Juan Viveros]]\n| [[Nissan Violet#A10|Datsun 160J]]\n|- style=\"background:#DDDDDD;\"\n| align=center | 1984<br>-<br>1988\n|COLSPAN=3| ''Not held''\n|-\n| 1989\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Alfredo Scheid]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 2.0]]\n|-\n| 1990\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Eduardo Elizeche]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 1.6]]\n|-\n| 1991\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Orlando Penner]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 1.8]]\n|-\n| 1992\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Pedro Fadul]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 1.8]]\n|-\n| 1993\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Orlando Penner]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 1.8]]\n|-\n| 1994\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Orlando Penner]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 2.0]]\n|-\n| 1995\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Marquito Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Celica GT-Four]]\n|-\n| 1996\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Marquito Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Celica GT-Four]]\n|-\n| 1997\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Marquito Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Celica GT-Four]]\n|-\n| 1998\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Alejandro Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Celica GT-Four]]\n|-\n| 1999\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Marquito Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla WRC]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Alejandro Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Celica GT-Four]]\n|-\n| 2001\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Francisco Gorostiaga]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla WRC]]\n|-\n| 2002\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Francisco Gorostiaga]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla WRC]]\n|-\n| 2003\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Francisco Gorostiaga]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla WRC]]\n|- style=\"background:#DDDDDD;\"\n| align=center | 2004<br>-<br>2005\n|COLSPAN=3| ''Not held''\n|-\n| 2006\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Alejandro Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla WRC]]\n|-\n| 2007\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Alejandro Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla WRC]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Victor Galeano]]\n| [[Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution|Mitsubishi Lancer Evo IX]]\n|-\n| 2009\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Alejandro Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla S2000]]\n|-\n| [[2010 Codasur South American Rally Championship|2010]]\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Alejandro Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla S2000]]\n|-\n| [[2011 Codasur South American Rally Championship|2011]]\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Tiago Weiler]]\n| [[Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution|Mitsubishi Lancer Evo IX]]\n|-\n| [[2012 Codasur South American Rally Championship|2012]]\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Alejandro Galanti]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla S2000]]\n|-\n| [[2013 Codasur South American Rally Championship|2013]]\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Gustavo Saba]]\n| [[\u0160koda Fabia S2000]]\n|-\n| [[2014 Codasur South American Rally Championship|2014]]\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Diego Dom\u00ednguez (rally driver)|Diego Dom\u00ednguez]]\n| [[Ford Fiesta R5]]\n|-\n|2015\n|{{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Gustavo Saba]]\n|[[\u0160koda Fabia S2000]]\n|-\n|2016\n|{{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Diego Dom\u00ednguez (rally driver)|Diego Dom\u00ednguez]]\n|[[Ford Fiesta R5]]\n|-\n|2017\n|{{Flagicon|ARG}} Marcos Ligato\n|[[\u0160koda Fabia R5]]\n|-\n|2018\n|{{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Diego Dom\u00ednguez (rally driver)|Diego Dom\u00ednguez]]\n|[[Hyundai i20 R5]]\n|-\n|2019\n|{{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Diego Dom\u00ednguez (rally driver)|Diego Dom\u00ednguez]]\n|[[Hyundai i20 R5]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://rally.com.py/ Paraguayan Rally Championship Official website]\n*[http://www.codasurfia.com/ CODASUR official website]\n\n[[Category:Codasur South American Rally Championship]]\n[[Category:Rally competitions in Paraguay]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Rally Trans Itapua''', is an international [[rally racing]] event based in the [[Itap\u00faa Department]] in south-east [[Paraguay]]. The event is the opening round of the [[Codasur South American Rally Championship]] and a round of the Paraguayan Championship, the [[Campeonato Nacional Paraguayo]].\n\nThe event was first run in 1981 and ran only briefly until 1983 as political instability swept Paraguay. Restart in 1989, the event has run continuously since then apart from a brief rest in 2004-05. The event became international in 2010 when it replaced the [[Rally de Encarnaci\u00f3n]] as Paraguay's rally on the CODASUR championship. Paraguayan drivers have won every event, even after the influx of international drivers of recent years. In particular the Galanti brothers have dominated the event. [[Alejandro Galanti]] has won the event seven times between 1998 and 2012 while older brother [[Marquito Galanti]] has taken four wins. All eleven victories were in Toyotas, spanning Group A, WRC and most recently Super 2000 technical regulations cars. 2008 saw Paraguay's first CODASUR champion Victor Galeano win the event. In 2013 triple Codasur champion [[Gustavo Saba]] finally broke through for a popular win at his home event.\n\n==List of winners==\nSourced in part from:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rally.com.py/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/itapua-2014.pdf |title=El Rally Trans Itap\u00faa, una prueba con historia |trans-title = The Rally Trans Itapua, a test with history |year=2014 |website= rally.com.py |publisher=Campeonato Nacional Paraguayo |lang = es |format=PDF |accessdate=2014-04-22 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year!!Winner!!Car\n|-\n| 1981\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Santiago Silguero]]\n| [[Nissan Violet#A10|Datsun 160J]]\n|-\n| 1982\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Santiago Silguero]]\n| [[Nissan Violet#A10|Datsun 160J]]\n|-\n| 1983\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Juan Viveros]]\n| [[Nissan Violet#A10|Datsun 160J]]\n|- style=\"background:#DDDDDD;\"\n| align=center | 1984<br>-<br>1988\n|COLSPAN=3| ''Not held''\n|-\n| 1989\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Alfredo Scheid]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 2.0]]\n|-\n| 1990\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Eduardo Elizeche]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 1.6]]\n|-\n| 1991\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Orlando Penner]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 1.8]]\n|-\n| 1992\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Pedro Fadul]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 1.8]]\n|-\n| 1993\n| {{Flagicon|PAR}} [[Orlando Penner]]\n| [[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf 1.8]