chive.org/web/20200331105559/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/morbius-ghostbusters-afterlife-uncharted-pushed-back-2021-sony-1203549616/|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Cinemas in 2020}}\n*BBC ''[[Talking Movies]]'', [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/entertainment-arts-51836542/coronavirus-puts-film-industry-in-turmoil Coronavirus puts film industry in 'turmoil'], March 12, 2020\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n[[Category:2020 in film]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema| ]]\n", "name_user": "Call me when you get the chance", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDelayed:Alphabetize", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_cinema"}
{"title_page": "Downtown Magnets High School", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name            = Downtown Magnets High School \n| other_names\t= Downtown Business Magnet\n| image           = Downtown Magnets High School (Los Angeles).jpg\n| streetaddress   = 1081 West Temple Street \n| city            = [[Los Angeles]]\n| state           = [[California]] \n| zipcode         = 90012 \n| country         = [[United States]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|34.062956|-118.250412|type:edu_globe:earth_region:US-CA|display=title,inline}}\n| type            = [[Magnet school|Magnet]], [[State school|Public]]\n| established     = 1981\n| district        = [[Los Angeles Unified School District|LAUSD]]\n| grades          = [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n| gender          = Coeducational\n| enrollment = 1056 (2019-2020)<ref>{{cite web|title = DMHS School Profile 2019-2020|url=https://4.files.edl.io/4489/11/08/19/160722-7466549a-e6d3-47d3-81a0-bcae0cdf64b7.pdf|publisher = Downtown Magnets|accessdate = 6 April 2020}}</ref>\n| grade9 = 265\n| grade10 = 288\n| grade11 = 268\n| grade12 = 235\n| ratio            = 21.87<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0622710&SchoolPageNum=19&ID=062271007757|title=Downtown Business High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| staff = 47.33 (FTE)<ref name=NCES></ref>\n| conference      = [[California Interscholastic Federation|CIF]] [[CIF Los Angeles City Section|Los Angeles City Section]]\n| mascot          = Sun\n| team_name       =\n| accreditation   = [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges|WASC]],<ref>{{citeweb|title=Accrediting Commission for Schools: Directory of schools 2014-2015|url=http://www.acswasc.org/pdf_general/ACS-WASC_Directory.pdf|publisher=[[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]|date=July 2014}}</ref> [[International Baccalaureate|IBO]]<ref name=\"IBO\">{{citeweb|title=IBO: Downtown Magnets High School|url=http://www.ibo.org/en/school/006435|publisher=[[International Baccalaureate Organisation]]}}</ref>\n| yearbook        =\n| alumni          = \n| website         = [http://www.downtownmagnets.org/  DMHS Official Website]\n| principal       = Dr. Sarah Usmani<ref>{{cite web|title=Principal's Message|url=https://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1039874&type=d&pREC_ID=1340799|publisher=Downtown Magnets High School LAUSD|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref>\n| enrollment_as_of=\n| colors          = Green and Gold <br /> {{color box|green}} {{color box|gold}}\n| newspaper = The Helios\n| national_ranking = 140<ref name = rank>{{cite web|title=Downtown Business High|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/california/districts/los-angeles-unified-school-district/downtown-business-high-2610|publisher=US News|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n| ranking = 15 (California)<ref name = rank/>\n| schedule_type = [[Block scheduling|block schedule]]\n}}\n\n'''Downtown Magnets High School''' (also known as '''DMHS''', Downtown Business Magnet, or DBM) is an [[Alternative school|alternate]] [[magnet school|magnet]] [[high school]] located in the Temple-Beaudry neighborhood near [[Downtown Los Angeles]].\n\nThe school houses three magnet programs: [[Business]] (DBM), and Electronic Information (EIM), and the [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB). The three magnets combined hold a total student population of approximately 1,000 students.\n\n==History==\n\nThe school was founded in 1981 with a specialization in business training. The school was named Downtown Business Magnet High School and was constructed near the [[Four-Level Interchange]] on the site of the defunct Custer Middle School. The school's first class consisted of 55 [[Tenth grade#United States|sophomore]]s from different neighborhoods around [[LAUSD]]. By 1994, FCC & EIM were formed.\n\n== Academics ==\nDMHS contains three magnet programs; Downtown Business Magnet (DBM), Electronic Information Magnet (EIM), and the International Baccalaureate (IB). \n\n=== Downtown Business Magnet (DBM) ===\nThe Downtown Business Magnet (DBM) was the first magnet program to be established at Downtown Magnets, and is the largest magnet program, with approximately 45% of the school's population. The curriculum includes Accounting, Business Organization, Corporate Management, Sales, Entrepreneurship, careers, international relations, and the use of technology in business.\n\nDBM houses two academies; Finance and Fashion Design & Merchandising.<ref name = DBM>{{cite web|title=Downtown Business Magnet (Business/Fashion)|publisher=Downtown Magnets|url=https://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1039874&type=d&pREC_ID=1359986|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Academy of Finance ====\nThe Academy of Finance (also known as the Academy of Business and Finance), is one of the Academies a part of DBM. It provides courses in entrepreneurship, accounting, corporate finance (financial planning), and international relations.\nThe Academy of Finance has been sponsored by [[CIT Group]], [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]], [[KPMG]], [[Cornerstone OnDemand]], and [[Cognizant]], and receives support from Los Angeles Education Partnership and the [[Network for Teaching Entrepreneurship]] with workshops, mock interviews, and internship opportunities.<ref name = DBM></ref>\n\nThe Academy of Finance offers six classes<ref name = catalog>{{cite web|title = DMHS Course Catalogue|url=https://www.downtownmagnets.org/ourpages/users/Robles/DMHS_Course_Catalogue_1.pdf|publisher=Downtown Magnets|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>:\n*Introduction to Business\n*Business Organization\n*Business Entrepreneurship\n*Advanced Accounting\n*[[International Relations]]\n*[[Corporate finance|Corporate Finance]]\n\n==== Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising ====\nThe Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising was established in 1992<ref name = LATimes>{{cite web|title=Drawn to the Magnets|date=24 December 2000|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2000-dec-24-me-4238-story.html|publisher =[[Los Angeles Times|LA Times]]|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> under the name \"Fashion Careers Center\" to educate students on the design and fabrication of general clothing [[apparel]]. In 2014, the Fashion Careers Center was combined along with the existing Academy of Finance of DBM. It was renamed the \"Academy of Fashion\" in 2015, and then to \"Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising\" in 2017.\n\nThe Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising has established partnerships with the [[Fashion Institute of Design and Merchandising]], [[Woodbury University]], [[Los Angeles Trade\u2013Technical College|L.A. Trade-Tech]], and the [[California Market Center]].<ref name = DBM></ref>\n\nThe Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising offers four classes<ref name = catalog></ref>:\n*[[Fashion illustration|Fashion Illustration]]\n*Beginning Clothing\n*Fashion Textiles and Apparel\n*Fashion Design and Fashion Management\n\n=== Electronic Information Magnet (EIM) ===\nThe Electronic Information Magnet (also known as Downtown Business Magnet (Computer Science/Engineering/Multimedia))<ref name = EIM>{{cite web|title=Downtown Business Magnet (Computer Science/Engineering/Multimedia)|url=https://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1039874&type=d&pREC_ID=1359988|publisher = Downtown Magnets|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> was established in 1994<ref name = LATimes></ref> has the second largest student population out of the three magnet programs and includes studies in [[Computer Science]], [[Computer Programming]] and [[Web Design]]. The magnet program was developed with the [[Los Angeles Central Library#Central Library|Los Angeles Central Library]] and the [[UCLA Graduate School of Education and Information Studies|UCLA Graduate School of Education]]<ref name = catalog></ref> in collaboration with several local business leaders and [[LAUSD]] Board Members. The program incorporates technology and [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] into students' high school educational processes.\n\nEIM holds a constant collaboration with the [[Los Angeles Central Library]]. Both DMHS and the Central Library are used as instruction sites. In addition to the Central Library, EIM shares a partnership with [[Los Angeles City College]] (LACC).\n\nEIM houses two academies; Information Technology and Engineering.\n\n==== Academy of Information Technology (AOIT) ==== \nThe Academy of Information Technology (AOIT) \nThe Academy of Information Technology offers six classes<ref name = catalog></ref>:\n*[[Computer Science]]\n*[[Digital imaging|Digital Imagery]]\n*Computer Progress\n*[[AP Computer Science]]\n*[[Filmmaking|Filmmaking]]\n*[[Yearbook]]\n\n==== Academy of Engineering (AOE)==== \nThe Academy of Engineering (AOE) uses the curriculum from [[Project Lead the Way]] to help students learn engineering concepts, design, and technology to solve real world problems.<ref>{{cite web|title=Academy of Engineering|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308180525/http://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=106983&type=d&pREC_ID=458716|publisher = Downtown Magnets|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Academy of Engineering offers four classes<ref name = catalog></ref>:\n*Introduction to Engineering Design\n*Principles of Engineering\n*Digital Electronics\n*Engineering Design and Development\n\n=== International Baccalaureate (IB) ===\nThe International Baccalaureate (IB) program was introduced to DMHS in 2014.\nSince the 2014-15 academic year, Downtown Magnets has offered the [[International Baccalaureate]] [[IB Diploma Programme|Diploma Program]]. Eleven subjects are offered:<ref name=\"IBO\"/>\n\n*English 1 / 2 HL\n*History 1 / 2 HL\n*Spanish / Spanish 1 HL\n*Math Studies / Math HL\n*Film 1 / 2 HL\n*Physics HL\n*Biology HL\n*Theory of Knowledge\n*H. Advanced Biology\n*H. Humanities\n*Mandarin SL\n\n=== Courses ===\nDowntown Magnets offers a variety of classes, Advanced Placement (AP) courses<ref>{{cite web|title=AP Courses|url=https://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1039889&type=d&pREC_ID=1340846|publisher = Downtown Magnets|accessdate = 6 April 2020}}</ref>, and Honors courses.\n\nAll areas of academic classes are offered at DMHS:\n\n*Science\n**[[Biology]]\n**[[Chemistry]]\n**[[Physics]]\n**[[AP Biology]]\n**[[AP Chemistry]]\n**[[AP Physics]]\n**[[AP Environmental Science]]\n\n*Arts\n**[[Visual arts education|Intro to Art]]\n**[[AP Art History]]\n**[[AP Studio Art]]\n\n*Mathematics\n**[[Mathematics education in the United States|Algebra I]]\n**[[Mathematics education in the United States|Geometry]]\n**[[Mathematics education in the United States|Algebra II]]\n**[[Trigonometry]]\n**[[AP Calculus|AP Calculus AB / BC]]\n**[[AP Statistics]]\n**Honors Advanced Math\n\n*English\n**Regular English\n**Honors English\n**[[AP English Literature]]\n**[[AP English Language]]\n**AP English Composition\n\n*Social Sciences\n**[[World History]]\n**[[US History]]\n**[[AP World History]]\n**[[AP US History]]\n**[[AP Human Geography]]\n**[[AP Psychology]]\n\n*Modern Languages\n**[[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n**Spanish Speakers\n**[[AP Spanish Language]]\n**[[AP Spanish Literature]]\n**[[AP Chinese Language and Culture|AP Chinese Language]]\n\n*Athletics \n**[[Physical education|Physical Education]] (at school, [[Elysian Park, Los Angeles|Elysian Park]], [[Echo Park, Los Angeles#Echo Park Lake|Echo Park Lake]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Students Take a Lap at Echo Park Lake as Street Closures for Sunday's Marathon Announced|url=https://patch.com/california/echopark/students-take-a-lap-at-echo-park-lake-as-street-closu5b7c32d61a|publisher=Patch|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>, or [[Griffith Park]])\n**Sports ([[Cross country running|Cross country]], [[Tennis]], [[Volleyball]], [[Basketball]], [[Association football|Soccer]], [[Softball]], and [[Track and field]])\n\n==Grings College Center==\n\nFor over 23 years, Carol Grings devoted her efforts to the Downtown Magnets College Center and other school programs.<ref name=\"Downtown Magnets High School college center\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=35495&type=u&rn=2963261 |title=Downtown Magnets High School |access-date=2009-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726003358/http://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=35495&type=u&rn=2963261 |archive-date=2011-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  When she died in 2005, the College Center was renamed the Grings College Center in her honor.\n\n== Academic Performance Index (API) ==\nThe [[Academic Performance Index]] (API) measures the academic progress of schools across the state of California.  Since the 2007-2008 school year, Downtown Magnets has placed number one in Local District 4 thanks to the continual growth of its API.  Its scores are as follows:\n\n{| cellpadding=\"10\" style=\"text-align: center; border: 1px solid silver;\"\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" | Year || '''2012''' || 2011 ||  2009 || 2008 || 2007 || 2005 || 2004 || 2003 || 2002 || 2001 || 2000 || 1999\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" | API  || '''826'''  || 807 || 746  || 736  || 690  || 655  || 645  || 616  || 606  || 601  || 593  || 595\n|}\n<small>The aforementioned data is provided by the California Department of Education.</small> <ref>{{cite web|title=Academic Performance Index (API) Report - Select Final Report Parameters|url=http://api.cde.ca.gov/reports/API/APISearchName.asp?TheYear=&cTopic=API&cLevel=School&cName=downtown^business&cCounty=&cTimeFrame=S|accessdate=16 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.downtownmagnets.org/}}\n*[http://www.lausd.net LAUSD Main Web page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110321160322/http://notebook.lausd.net/portal/page?_pageid=33,54194&_dad=ptl&_schema=PTL_EP LAUSD DBM INFO]\