 school houses three magnet progrems: [[Business]] (DBM), and Electronic Information (EIM), and the [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB). The three magnets combined hold a total student population of approximately 1,000 students.\n\n==History==\n\nThe school was founded in 1981 with a specialization in business training. The school was named Downtown Business Magnet High School and was constructed near the [[Four-Level Interchange]] on the site of the defunct Custer Middle School. The school's first class consisted of 55 [[Tenth grade#United States|sophomore]]s from different neighborhoods around [[LAUSD]]. By 1994, FCC & EIM were formed.\n\n== Academics ==\nDMHS contains three magnet programs; Downtown Business Magnet (DBM), Electronic Information Magnet (EIM), and the International Baccalaureate (IB). \n\n=== Downtown Business Magnet (DBM) ===\nThe Downtown Business Magnet (DBM) was the first magnet program to be established at Downtown Magnets, and is the largest magnet program, with approximately 45% of the school's population. The curriculum includes Accounting, Business Organization, Corporate Management, Sales, Entrepreneurship, careers, international relations, and the use of technology in business.\n\nDBM houses two academies; Finance and Fashion Design & Merchandising.<ref name = DBM>{{cite web|title=Downtown Business Magnet (Business/Fashion)|publisher=Downtown Magnets|url=https://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1039874&type=d&pREC_ID=1359986|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Academy of Finance ====\nThe Academy of Finance (also known as the Academy of Business and Finance), is one of the Academies a part of DBM. It provides courses in entrepreneurship, accounting, corporate finance (financial planning), and international relations.\nThe Academy of Finance has been sponsored by [[CIT Group]], [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]], [[KPMG]], [[Cornerstone OnDemand]], and [[Cognizant]], and receives support from Los Angeles Education Partnership and the [[Network for Teaching Entrepreneurship]] with workshops, mock interviews, and internship opportunities.<ref name = DBM></ref>\n\nThe Academy of Finance offers six classes<ref name = catalog>{{cite web|title = DMHS Course Catalogue|url=https://www.downtownmagnets.org/ourpages/users/Robles/DMHS_Course_Catalogue_1.pdf|publisher=Downtown Magnets|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>:\n*Introduction to Business\n*Business Organization\n*Business Entrepreneurship\n*Advanced Accounting\n*[[International Relations]]\n*[[Corporate finance|Corporate Finance]]\n\n==== Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising ====\nThe Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising was established in 1992<ref name = LATimes>{{cite web|title=Drawn to the Magnets|date=24 December 2000|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2000-dec-24-me-4238-story.html|publisher =[[Los Angeles Times|LA Times]]|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> under the name \"Fashion Careers Center\" to educate students on the design and fabrication of general clothing [[apparel]]. In 2014, the Fashion Careers Center was combined along with the existing Academy of Finance of DBM. It was renamed the \"Academy of Fashion\" in 2015, and then to \"Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising\" in 2017.\n\nThe Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising has established partnerships with the [[Fashion Institute of Design and Merchandising]], [[Woodbury University]], [[Los Angeles Trade\u2013Technical College|L.A. Trade-Tech]], and the [[California Market Center]].<ref name = DBM></ref>\n\nThe Academy of Fashion Design & Merchandising offers four classes<ref name = catalog></ref>:\n*[[Fashion illustration|Fashion Illustration]]\n*Beginning Clothing\n*Fashion Textiles and Apparel\n*Fashion Design and Fashion Management\n\n=== Electronic Information Magnet (EIM) ===\nThe Electronic Information Magnet (also known as Downtown Business Magnet (Computer Science/Engineering/Multimedia))<ref name = EIM>{{cite web|title=Downtown Business Magnet (Computer Science/Engineering/Multimedia)|url=https://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1039874&type=d&pREC_ID=1359988|publisher = Downtown Magnets|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> was established in 1994<ref name = LATimes></ref> has the second largest student population out of the three magnet programs and includes studies in [[Computer Science]], [[Computer Programming]] and [[Web Design]]. The magnet program was developed with the [[Los Angeles Central Library#Central Library|Los Angeles Central Library]] and the [[UCLA Graduate School of Education and Information Studies|UCLA Graduate School of Education]]<ref name = catalog></ref> in collaboration with several local business leaders and [[LAUSD]] Board Members. The program incorporates technology and [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] into students' high school educational processes.\n\nEIM holds a constant collaboration with the [[Los Angeles Central Library]]. Both DMHS and the Central Library are used as instruction sites. In addition to the Central Library, EIM shares a partnership with [[Los Angeles City College]] (LACC).\n\nEIM houses two academies; Information Technology and Engineering.\n\n==== Academy of Information Technology (AOIT) ==== \nThe Academy of Information Technology (AOIT) \nThe Academy of Information Technology offers six classes<ref name = catalog></ref>:\n*[[Computer Science]]\n*[[Digital imaging|Digital Imagery]]\n*Computer Progress\n*[[AP Computer Science]]\n*[[Filmmaking|Filmmaking]]\n*[[Yearbook]]\n\n==== Academy of Engineering (AOE)==== \nThe Academy of Engineering (AOE) uses the curriculum from [[Project Lead the Way]] to help students learn engineering concepts, design, and technology to solve real world problems.<ref>{{cite web|title=Academy of Engineering|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308180525/http://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=106983&type=d&pREC_ID=458716|publisher = Downtown Magnets|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Academy of Engineering offers four classes<ref name = catalog></ref>:\n*Introduction to Engineering Design\n*Principles of Engineering\n*Digital Electronics\n*Engineering Design and Development\n\n=== International Baccalaureate (IB) ===\nThe International Baccalaureate (IB) program was introduced to DMHS in 2014.\nSince the 2014-15 academic year, Downtown Magnets has offered the [[International Baccalaureate]] [[IB Diploma Programme|Diploma Program]]. Eleven subjects are offered:<ref name=\"IBO\"/>\n\n*English 1 / 2 HL\n*History 1 / 2 HL\n*Spanish / Spanish 1 HL\n*Math Studies / Math HL\n*Film 1 / 2 HL\n*Physics HL\n*Biology HL\n*Theory of Knowledge\n*H. Advanced Biology\n*H. Humanities\n*Mandarin SL\n\n=== Courses ===\nDowntown Magnets offers a variety of classes, Advanced Placement (AP) courses<ref>{{cite web|title=AP Courses|url=https://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1039889&type=d&pREC_ID=1340846|publisher = Downtown Magnets|accessdate = 6 April 2020}}</ref>, and Honors courses.\n\nAll areas of academic classes are offered at DMHS:\n\n*Science\n**[[Biology]]\n**[[Chemistry]]\n**[[Physics]]\n**[[AP Biology]]\n**[[AP Chemistry]]\n**[[AP Physics]]\n**[[AP Environmental Science]]\n\n*Arts\n**[[Visual arts education|Intro to Art]]\n**[[AP Art History]]\n**[[AP Studio Art]]\n\n*Mathematics\n**[[Mathematics education in the United States|Algebra I]]\n**[[Mathematics education in the United States|Geometry]]\n**[[Mathematics education in the United States|Algebra II]]\n**[[Trigonometry]]\n**[[AP Calculus|AP Calculus AB / BC]]\n**[[AP Statistics]]\n**Honors Advanced Math\n\n*English\n**Regular English\n**Honors English\n**[[AP English Literature]]\n**[[AP English Language]]\n**AP English Composition\n\n*Social Sciences\n**[[World History]]\n**[[US History]]\n**[[AP World History]]\n**[[AP US History]]\n**[[AP Human Geography]]\n**[[AP Psychology]]\n\n*Modern Languages\n**[[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n**Spanish Speakers\n**[[AP Spanish Language]]\n**[[AP Spanish Literature]]\n**[[AP Chinese Language and Culture|AP Chinese Language]]\n\n*Athletics \n**[[Physical education|Physical Education]] (at school, [[Elysian Park, Los Angeles|Elysian Park]], [[Echo Park, Los Angeles#Echo Park Lake|Echo Park Lake]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Students Take a Lap at Echo Park Lake as Street Closures for Sunday's Marathon Announced|url=https://patch.com/california/echopark/students-take-a-lap-at-echo-park-lake-as-street-closu5b7c32d61a|publisher=Patch|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>, or [[Griffith Park]])\n**Sports ([[Cross country running|Cross country]], [[Tennis]], [[Volleyball]], [[Basketball]], [[Association football|Soccer]], [[Softball]], and [[Track and field]])\n\n==Grings College Center==\n\nFor over 23 years, Carol Grings devoted her efforts to the Downtown Magnets College Center and other school programs.<ref name=\"Downtown Magnets High School college center\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=35495&type=u&rn=2963261 |title=Downtown Magnets High School |access-date=2009-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726003358/http://www.downtownmagnets.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=35495&type=u&rn=2963261 |archive-date=2011-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  When she died in 2005, the College Center was renamed the Grings College Center in her honor.\n\n== Academic Performance Index (API) ==\nThe [[Academic Performance Index]] (API) measures the academic progress of schools across the state of California.  Since the 2007-2008 school year, Downtown Magnets has placed number one in Local District 4 thanks to the continual growth of its API.  Its scores are as follows:\n\n{| cellpadding=\"10\" style=\"text-align: center; border: 1px solid silver;\"\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" | Year || '''2012''' || 2011 ||  2009 || 2008 || 2007 || 2005 || 2004 || 2003 || 2002 || 2001 || 2000 || 1999\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"silver\" | API  || '''826'''  || 807 || 746  || 736  || 690  || 655  || 645  || 616  || 606  || 601  || 593  || 595\n|}\n<small>The aforementioned data is provided by the California Department of Education.</small> <ref>{{cite web|title=Academic Performance Index (API) Report - Select Final Report Parameters|url=http://api.cde.ca.gov/reports/API/APISearchName.asp?TheYear=&cTopic=API&cLevel=School&cName=downtown^business&cCounty=&cTimeFrame=S|accessdate=16 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.downtownmagnets.org/}}\n*[http://www.lausd.net LAUSD Main Web page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110321160322/http://notebook.lausd.net/portal/page?_pageid=33,54194&_dad=ptl&_schema=PTL_EP LAUSD DBM INFO]\n*[http://search.lausd.k12.ca.us/cgi-bin/fccgi.exe?w3exec=find3&which=8746 Detailed School Information]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070711040216/http://www.lapl.org/central/eimhs.html Los Angeles Central Library]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/dmhsla DMHS ASB Myspace Page]\n\n{{LAUSD}}\n\n[[Category:Los Angeles Unified School District schools]]\n[[Category:High schools in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Downtown Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in California]]\n[[Category:Magnet schools in California]]\n[[Category:Alternative schools in California]]\n[[Category:Chinatown, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1981]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in California]]\n", "name_user": "ItsJustReppopz", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed spelling error that I made.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Downtown_Magnets_High_School"}
{"title_page": "The Modernaires", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = The Modernaires\n| image           = The Modernaires 1951.JPG\n| image_size      = 240\n| caption         = The Modernaires when they were regulars on the CBS radio program ''[[Club Fifteen]]'', 1951.\n| background      = group_or_band\n| genre           = [[Swing music]], [[Vocal music]]\n| years_active    = {{Start date|1934}}\u20131970s\n| label           = [[Bluebird Records]]\n| associated_acts = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Glenn Miller]]\n* [[Glenn Miller Orchestra]]\n* [[Paul Whiteman]]\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.themodernaires.com}}\n| current_members = \n| past_members    = \n* [[Paula Kelly (singer)|Paula Kelly]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224926212 |title=Well- Known Vocal Quintet Featured in New Musical |newspaper=[[Weekly Times]] |issue=4248 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=22 November 1950 |accessdate=3 June 2018 |page=55 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n* Hal Dickinson\n* Chuck Goldstein\n* Ralph Brewster\n* Bill Conway\n* Fran Scott\n* Johnny Drake\n* [[Alan Copeland]]\n* Paula Kelly (Junior)<!-- daughter of Paula Kelly--><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article126893434 |title=MUSIC Glenn Miller tribute |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=56 |issue=17,020 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=4 May 1982 |accessdate=3 June 2018 |page=25 |via=National Library of Australia}} , ''...Also featured will be Paula Kelly, junior, and the Modernaires, today's version of the vocal group...''</ref>\n}}\n'''The Modernaires''' were an [[United States|American]] [[vocal group]], best known for performing in the 1940s alongside [[Glenn Miller]].\n\n==Career==\nThe Modernaires began in 1934 as \"Don Juan, Two and Three,\" a trio of schoolmates from [[Lafayette High School (Buffalo)|Lafayette High School]] in [[Buffalo, New York]]. The members were Hal Dickinson, Chuck Goldstein, and Bill Conway.<ref name=\"asg\">{{cite book|last1=Warner|first1=Jay|title=American Singing Groups: A History from 1940s to Today|date=2006|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|isbn=9780634099786|pages=[https://archive.org/details/americansingingg00warn/page/49 49]\u201351|url=https://archive.org/details/americansingingg00warn|url-access=registration|quote=Paula Kelly singer.|accessdate=December 15, 2016|language=en}}</ref> (Jay Warner, in his book ''American Singing Groups: A History from 1940s to Today'', wrote, \"They called themselves Three Weary Willies\".{{r|asg|page1=49}} He added that the trio performed as Don Juan and Two and Three when they \"headed for New York in the mid-'30s\".){{r|asg|page1=50}}\n\nAfter singing on radio station [[WGR]] in Buffalo, New York, for \"the enormous sum of $10 a month\", the trio went to New York City and gained an engagement of 26 weeks on [[CBS]] network radio.{{r|asg|page1=50}}\n\nThe group's first engagement was at Buffalo's suburban Glen Falls Casino, with the [[Ted Fio Rito|Ted Fio Rito Orchestra]]. Fio Rito also used them on [[electrical transcription]] recordings. They then joined the [[Ozzie Nelson]] Band, and became known as \"The Three Wizards of Ozzie.\" They next recruited Ralph Brewster to make a quartet and, performing with the [[Fred Waring]] Orchestra, became The Modern-Aires (later changing the spelling). Recordings with [[Charlie Barnet]]'s orchestra in 1936 did not interest the public but brought them greater industry exposure, and in 1937 they joined the [[George Hall (musician)|George Hall]] band, soon moving on to the [[Paul Whiteman]] radio show. They recorded many of the classic songs of that era, a few with [[Jack Teagarden]], as part of the Whiteman orchestra in 1938.\n\nIn October 1940, [[Glenn Miller]] engaged them to record ''It's Make Believe Ballroom Time'', a sequel to the original ''Make Believe Ballroom,'' which they had recorded earlier for [[Martin Block]]'s [[big band]] show of the same name, on [[WBBR|WNEW]] New York. In January 1941, Miller made The Modernaires an important part of one of the most popular big bands of all time. [[Paula Kelly (singer)|Paula Kelly]] was added to the Miller band between March\u2013August 1941; she and Modernaire Hal Dickinson had married in 1939. The group had ten chart hits in 1941 after appearing with Miller's orchestra in the movie ''[[Sun Valley Serenade]]''. The group became a quintet when Kelly became a permanent member of the group after Miller joined the [[U.S. Army]], and for the next few decades they toured internationally with the [[Glenn Miller Orchestra]]. Johnny Drake replaced Chuck Goldstein (who left the Modernaires the day after the Miller band broke up in 1942), and Fran Scott replaced Bill Conway (who by fall 1943 was performing with the newly-formed \"Double Daters\" quartet<ref>Kaplan, Ben. \"For the Love of Mike.\" Richmond (VA) Times-Dispatch, 14 September 1943.</ref>).\n\nSongs made popular by Miller and The Modernaires included \"[[Perfidia]],\" \"[[Chattanooga Choo-Choo]],\" with [[Tex Beneke]] (the first-ever \"gold record\" with over one million copies sold), \"I Know Why,\" \"Elmer's Tune,\" \"[[Serenade In Blue]],\" \"Connecticut,\" and \"Kalamazoo\" with Beneke, among others.\n\nIn 1945, \"[[There! I've Said It Again]]\" became The Modernaires' first top-twenty hit.\n\nThe group was featured in television programming produced by [[Philco]] in 1947, using what apparently was an early version of [[lip synch|lip synching]]. An article in Variety magazine's September 10, 1947, issue reported that David Street and The Modernaires guest starred on the Philco program, \"simulating singing to off-screen recordings.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Philco's New Coast Tele Shows Offer Welcome Change from Old Ideas|url=https://archive.org/stream/variety167-1947-09#page/n85/mode/2up/search/%22David+Street%22|accessdate=July 23, 2016|work=Variety|date=September 10, 1947|page=30}}</ref> \n\nAfter Miller's disappearance, The Modernaires recorded vocal versions of several of Miller's instrumental hits, including \"[[Moonlight Serenade]]\", \"[[Sunrise Serenade]]\", \"[[Little Brown Jug (song)|Little Brown Jug]]\", \"[[Tuxedo Junction]]\", \"[[Pennsylvania 6-5000]]\", and \"[[A String of Pearls (song)|A String of Pearls]]\". The Modernaires released a [[45rpm single]] on Coral Records, 9-61110, A Salute to Glenn Miller, which included medleys in two parts from the movie soundtrack, A Salute to Glenn Miller, Parts 1 and 2: (I've Got a Gal In) Kalamazoo/Moonlight Cocktail/Elmer's Tune/Moonlight Serenade/Chattanooga Choo-Choo/String Of Pearls/Serenade In Blue/At Last/Perfidia, that reached number 29 on the Billboard charts in 1954. In the late 1950s they were featured vocalists with the [[Bob Crosby|Bob Crosby Orchestra]] on his daily TV show. In the 60s they recorded the theme song for the TV sitcom [[Hazel (TV series)|Hazel]]. Their style, harmonies and blend influenced later artists such as [[The Four Freshmen]], who in turn were models for the [[Beach Boys]], whom the [[Beatles]] later cited as a strong influence on their work. Thus, The Modernaires have affected generations of popular music, from swing to rock and roll. The Modernaires were inducted into The [[Vocal Group Hall of Fame]] in 1999.\n\n== Whereabouts of members ==\nHal Dickinson ''(n\u00e9'' Harold Hunt Dickinson, Jr.; 1913\u20131970) died in [[Santa Barbara, California]].<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/53667627/harold-h.-dickinson Find A Grave: Harold H. Dickinson, Jr]</ref> His wife, [[Paula Kelly (singer)|Paula Kelly]] (1919\u20131992), died in [[Costa Mesa, California]].<ref name=\"Folkart\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-04/news/mn-104_1_glenn-miller|title=Paula Kelly; Sang With Modernaires, Glenn Miller|last=Folkart|first=Burt A.|date=April 4, 1992|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> Their daughter, Paula Dickinson Kelly, Jr. (1944\u20132012), who took over signing her mother's parts with the Modernaires from 1966 to 1971, died in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>[https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/latimes/obituary.aspx?n=paula-kelly-cole&pid=157531569 Paula Kelly Cole obituary]</ref> Chuck Goldstein, born in [[Buffalo, New York]] ''(n\u00e9'' Charles J. Goldstein; 1914\u20131974), died in [[Englewood, New Jersey]].<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/artist/2517725-Chuck-Goldstein Discogs: Chuck Goldstein profile]</ref> Conway ''(n\u00e9'' William G. Conway; 1913\u20131991) died in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/3698603/william-g-conway Find A Grave: William G \u201cBill\u201d Conway]</ref> Ralph Brewster ''(n\u00e9'' Ralph Fletcher Brewster; 1914\u20131990) died in [[Tulsa]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927040614/http://www.vocalgroup.org/inductees/the_modernaires.html 'The Modernaires' Vocal Group Hall of Fame Page]\n* [http://www.singers.com/jazz/vintage/modernaires.html Page on The Modernaires]\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20060221235109/http://www.parabrisas.com/d_modernaires.php\n\n{{Glenn Miller}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Modernaires}}\n[[Category:Musical groups from Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1935]]\n[[Category:American vocal groups]]\n[[Category:American jazz ensembles]]\n[[Category:Vocal jazz ensembles]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Glenn Miller Orchestra members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = The Modernaires\n| image           = The Modernaires 1951.JPG\n| image_size      = 240\n| caption         = The Modernaires when they were regulars on the CBS radio program ''[[Club Fifteen]]'', 1951.\n| background      = group_or_band\n| genre           = [[Swing music]], [[Vocal music]]\n| years_active    = {{Start date|1934}}\u20131970s\n| label           = [[Bluebird Records]]\n| associated_acts = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Glenn Miller]]\n* [[Glenn Miller Orchestra]]\n* [[Paul Whiteman]]\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.themodernaires.com}}\n| current_members = \n| past_members    = \n* [[Paula Kelly (singer)|Paula Kelly]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224926212 |title=Well- Known Vocal Quintet Featured in New Musical |newspaper=[[Weekly Times]] |issue=4248 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=22 November 1950 |accessdate=3 June 2018 |page=55 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n* Hal Dickinson\n* Chuck Goldstein\n* Ralph Brewster\n* Bill Conway\n* Fran Scott\n* Johnny Drake\n* [[Alan Copeland]]\n* Paula Kelly (Junior)<!-- daughter of Paula Kelly--><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article126893434 |title=MUSIC Glenn Miller tribute |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=56 |issue=17,020 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=4 May 1982 |accessdate=3 June 2018 |page=25 |via=National Library of Australia}} , ''...Also featured will be Paula Kelly, junior, and the Modernaires, today's version of the vocal group...''</ref>\n}}\n'''The Modernaires''' were an [[United States|American]] [[vocal group]], best known for performing in the 1940s alongside [[Glenn Miller]].\n\n==Career==\nThe Modernaires began in 1934 as \"Don Juan, Two and Three,\" a trio of schoolmates from [[Lafayette High School (Buffalo)|Lafayette High School]] in [[Buffalo, New York]]. The members were Hal Dickinson, Chuck Goldstein, and Bill Conway.<ref name=\"asg\">{{cite book|last1=Warner|first1=Jay|title=American Singing Groups: A History from 1940s to Today|date=2006|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|isbn=9780634099786|pages=[https://archive.org/details/americansingingg00warn/page/49 49]\u201351|url=https://archive.org/details/americansingingg00warn|url-access=registration|quote=Paula Kelly singer.|accessdate=December 15, 2016|language=en}}</ref> (Jay Warner, in his book ''American Singing Groups: A History from 1940s to Today'', wrote, \"They called themselves Three Weary Willies\".{{r|asg|page1=49}} He added that the trio performed as Don Juan and Two and Three when they \"headed for New York in the mid-'30s\".){{r|asg|page1=50}}\n\nAfter singing on radio station [[WGR]] in Buffalo, New York, for \"the enormous sum of $10 a month\", the trio went to New York City and gained an engagement of 26 weeks on [[CBS]] network radio.{{r|asg|page1=50}}\n\nThe group's first engagement was at Buffalo's suburban Glen Falls Casino, with the [[Ted Fio Rito|Ted Fio Rito Orchestra]]. Fio Rito also used them on [[electrical transcription]] recordings. They then joined the [[Ozzie Nelson]] Band, and became known as \"The Three Wizards of Ozzie.\" They next recruited Ralph Brewster to make a quartet and, performing with the [[Fred Waring]] Orchestra, became The Modern-Aires (later changing the spelling). Recordings with [[Charlie Barnet]]'s orchestra in 1936 did not interest the public but brought them greater industry exposure, and in 1937 they joined the [[George Hall (musician)|George Hall]] band, soon moving on to the [[Paul Whiteman]] radio show. They recorded many of the classic songs of that era, a few with [[Jack Teagarden]], as part of the Whiteman orchestra in 1938.\n\nIn October 1940, [[Glenn Miller]] engaged them to record ''It's Make Believe Ballroom Time'', a sequel to the original ''Make Believe Ballroom,'' which they had recorded earlier for [[Martin Block]]'s [[big band]] show of the same name, on [[WBBR|WNEW]] New York. In January 1941, Miller made The Modernaires an important part of one of the most popular big bands of all time. [[Paula Kelly (singer)|Paula Kelly]] was added to the Miller band between March\u2013August 1941; she and Modernaire Hal Dickinson had married in 1939. The group had ten chart hits in 1941 after appearing with Miller's orchestra in the movie ''[[Sun Valley Serenade]]''. The group became a quintet when Kelly became a permanent member of the group after Miller joined the [[U.S. Army]], and for the next few decades they toured internationally with the [[Glenn Miller Orchestra]]. Johnny Drake replaced Chuck Goldstein (who left the Modernaires the day after the Miller band broke up in 1942), and Fran Scott replaced Bill Conway (who left during the war and never returned to the group).{{citation needed|date=February 2010}}\n\nSongs made popular by Miller and The Modernaires included \"[[Perfidia]],\" \"[[Chattanooga Choo-Choo]],\" with [[Tex Beneke]] (the first-ever \"gold record\" with over one million copies sold), \"I Know Why,\" \"Elmer's Tune,\" \"[[Serenade In Blue]],\" \"Connecticut,\" and \"Kalamazoo\" with Beneke, among others.\n\nIn 1945, \"[[There! I've Said It Again]]\" became The Modernaires' first top-twenty hit.\n\nThe group was featured in television programming produced by [[Philco]] in 1947, using what apparently was an early version of [[lip synch|lip synching]]. An article in Variety magazine's September 10, 1947, issue reported that David Street and The Modernaires guest starred on the Philco program, \"simulating singing to off-screen recordings.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Philco's New Coast Tele Shows Offer Welcome Change from Old Ideas|url=https://archive.org/stream/variety167-1947-09#page/n85/mode/2up/search/%22David+Street%22|accessdate=July 23, 2016|work=Variety|date=September 10, 1947|page=30}}</ref> \n\nAfter Miller's disappearance, The Modernaires recorded vocal versions of several of Miller's instrumental hits, including \"[[Moonlight Serenade]]\", \"[[Sunrise Serenade]]\", \"[[Little Brown Jug (song)|Little Brown Jug]]\", \"[[Tuxedo Junction]]\", \"[[Pennsylvania 6-5000]]\", and \"[[A String of Pearls (song)|A String of Pearls]]\". The Modernaires released a [[45rpm single]] on Coral Records, 9-61110, A Salute to Glenn Miller, which included medleys in two parts from the movie soundtrack, A Salute to Glenn Miller, Parts 1 and 2: (I've Got a Gal In) Kalamazoo/Moonlight Cocktail/Elmer's Tune/Moonlight Serenade/Chattanooga Choo-Choo/String Of Pearls/Serenade In Blue/At Last/Perfidia, that reached number 29 on the Billboard charts in 1954. In the late 1950s they were featured vocalists with the [[Bob Crosby|Bob Crosby Orchestra]] on his daily TV show. In the 60s they recorded the theme song for the TV sitcom [[Hazel (TV series)|Hazel]]. Their style, harmonies and blend influenced later artists such as [[The Four Freshmen]], who in turn were models for the [[Beach Boys]], whom the [[Beatles]] later cited as a strong influence on their work. Thus, The Modernaires have affected generations of popular music, from swing to rock and roll. The Modernaires were inducted into The [[Vocal Group Hall of Fame]] in 1999.\n\n== Whereabouts of members ==\nHal Dickinson ''(n\u00e9'' Harold Hunt Dickinson, Jr.; 1913\u20131970) died in [[Santa Barbara, California]].<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/53667627/harold-h.-dickinson Find A Grave: Harold H. Dickinson, Jr]</ref> His wife, [[Paula Kelly (singer)|Paula Kelly]] (1919\u20131992), died in [[Costa Mesa, California]].<ref name=\"Folkart\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-04/news/mn-104_1_glenn-miller|title=Paula Kelly; Sang With Modernaires, Glenn Miller|last=Folkart|first=Burt A.|date=April 4, 1992|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> Their daughter, Paula Dickinson Kelly, Jr. (1944\u20132012), who took over signing her mother's parts with the Modernaires from 1966 to 1971, died in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>[https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/latimes/obituary.aspx?n=paula-kelly-cole&pid=157531569 Paula Kelly Cole obituary]</ref> Chuck Goldstein, born in [[Buffalo, New York]] ''(n\u00e9'' Charles J. Goldstein; 1914\u20131974), died in [[Englewood, New Jersey]].<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/artist/2517725-Chuck-Goldstein Discogs: Chuck Goldstein profile]</ref> Conway ''(n\u00e9'' William G. Conway; 1913\u20131991) died in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/3698603/william-g-conway Find A Grave: William G \u201cBill\u201d Conway]</ref> Ralph Brewster ''(n\u00e9'' Ralph Fletcher Brewster; 1914\u20131990) died in [[Tulsa]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927040614/http://www.vocalgroup.org/inductees/the_modernaires.html 'The Modernaires' Vocal Group Hall of Fame Page]\n* [http://www.singers.com/jazz/vintage/modernaires.html Page on The Modernaires]\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20060221235109/http://www.parabrisas.com/d_modernaires.php\n\n{{Glenn Miller}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Modernaires}}\n[[Category:Musical groups from Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1935]]\n[[Category:American vocal groups]]\n[[Category:American jazz ensembles]]\n[[Category:Vocal jazz ensembles]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Glenn Miller Orchestra members]]\n", "name_user": "20thCenturyAmMusic", "label": "safe", "comment": "D", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Modernaires"}
